# Framer Code Component Conventions

When creating or editing Framer Code Components in this repo, follow these rules.

## 1. Default export and Framer tags

- **Export the component as a default function**: use `export default function ComponentName(...)`, not `export function ComponentName` or `export const ComponentName`.
- **Put Framer tags immediately above the export**: add a JSDoc block with the Framer annotations **directly above** the `export default function` declaration (no other code in between). Example:

```ts
/**
 * @framerSupportedLayoutWidth any-prefer-fixed
 * @framerSupportedLayoutHeight any-prefer-fixed
 * @framerIntrinsicWidth 400
 * @framerIntrinsicHeight 300
 * @framerDisableUnlink
 */
export default function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps) {
```

## 2. Build components as in how-to-build-framer-components/

- Follow the patterns and structure described in **how-to-build-framer-components/** (especially `framer-uni.md`).
- Use the guides for: component structure, property controls order, value mapping, empty states, mouse/pointer events (`mouseAndPointerEvents.md`), and color handling in the Framer canvas.
- For external libraries, bundle them as in **custom-bundle-gsap/readme.md** and host the built `dist/bundle.js`. **Import from the bundle at the top of the component file** (same pattern as DepthGlobe, etc.). **Never** add a bundle URL as a property control — bundle imports always go in the file header.

## 3. Bundled code: import at top, never as a property

- **Always** import from the hosted bundle **at the top of the file**, e.g. `import { WebHaptics } from "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/framer-university/components/npm-bundles/haptics.js"`.
- **Never** add a bundle-URL property control. Users do not configure bundle URLs; the component file has the import URL.

## 4. Single-word titles for property controls

Use **single-word** `title` values in `addPropertyControls` where possible.

- Prefer: `title: "Preview"`, `title: "Preset"`, `title: "Debug"`, `title: "Speed"`.
- Avoid: `title: "Bundle URL"` → use `title: "Bundle"` (or "URL"); `title: "Custom pattern"` → use `title: "Pattern"`.
- For grouped or nested controls, keep each control’s title to one word when it still reads clearly.

## 5. Framer University link in the last property control

**Always** add the Framer University link to the **last** property control in `addPropertyControls`:

```ts
// Last control in addPropertyControls(ComponentName, { ... })
debug: {
    type: ControlType.Boolean,
    title: "Debug",
    defaultValue: false,
    description: "More components at [Framer University](https://frameruni.link/cc).",
},
```

Use the exact link: **https://frameruni.link/cc**

## 6. Property control descriptions

- **Don’t add descriptions** unless needed. Only the following should have a `description`:
  - The **last** property control (must include the Framer University link).
  - Other controls that need a **URL** (e.g. where users paste a link) — not bundle URLs; those are never props.
- When you do use a description, keep it **as short as possible** (one short sentence or a few words).

## 7. PROPERTIES.txt for every new component

When you **create a new** Framer Code Component:

- Add a **PROPERTIES.txt** file in the **same folder** as the component (e.g. `next-dev/app/MyComponent/PROPERTIES.txt`).
- List each property control with a short description, in the same order as in the component.
- End the file with a line that includes the Framer University link (e.g. "More components at Framer University" or the full sentence used in the last prop).

Example layout:

```
ComponentName - Property Controls

Preview
Whether the effect runs in the Framer canvas. On / Off.

Preset
Built-in pattern. Options: …

Framer
… More components at Framer University.
```

## 8. displayName at the bottom of the file

**Always** set a `displayName` on the exported component, at the **bottom** of the file (after `addPropertyControls`):

```ts
addPropertyControls(ComponentName, { ... })

ComponentName.displayName = "Human Readable Name"
```

Use a short, readable label (e.g. `"Haptics"`, `"Letter Testimonial"`, `"Pixel Mask Reveal"`). This is what Framer shows in the components panel.
